* cwltool version: 1.0.20170824143724

I have an interesting use-case which doesn't seem possible with `graphene-django` out of the box. I'm fairly new to Python, so this may be frowned upon or I'm missing a simple implementation. Nevertheless-

In our application layer we have a single `django.db.models.Model` which has a special field which indicates its "type" to the rest of the app. It's a large legacy codebase, so there are lots of places where this "type" is checked and acted upon.

What I now want to do is have a `DjangoObjectType` in my schema that lets me declare fields & lists using the base `graphene.Interface` which is smart enough to figure out which objects are which. So I've implemented a metaclass as follows:

```
class AgentMeta(DjangoObjectTypeMeta):
    def __instancecheck__(self, other):
        if self.is_context and other == Organization:
            return True
        if not self.is_context and other == Person:
            return True
        return DjangoObjectTypeMeta.__instancecheck__(self, other)
```

So far so good. But if I try to do:

```
@add_metaclass(AgentMeta)
class Agent(graphene.Interface):
```

I get an error, because `DjangoObjectType` inherits from `graphene.ObjectType`, not `graphene.Interface`- so the metaclasses aren't from the same superclass and it won't compile.

Is there a way to get this behaviour? Even if I have to implement a parsing step to iterate over all objects in my `resolve_*` functions, I'm totally happy to accept that performance penalty.

...otherwise, I'll probably just end up copying the bulk of `DjangoObjectType` and hacking it to my needs, but I wanted to be sure there wasn't a way that would let me continue to recieve patches & updates from this repo first.

There is an error when using shared modules with multiple threads where the module can be shared before it has finished initializing. This results in missing attributes. The following code can be used to demonstrate the error. 

```java
import java.util.function.Consumer;
import jep.Jep;
import jep.JepConfig;

import java.lang.Thread;
import java.lang.Exception;


public class Test extends Thread{

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Throwable{
        Test[] t = new Test[10];
        for(int i = 0 ; i < t.length ; i += 1){
            t[i] = new Test();
            t[i].start();
        }
        for(int i = 0 ; i < t.length ; i += 1){
            t[i].join();
        }
    }

    @Override
    public void run() {
        try(Jep jep = new Jep(new JepConfig().addSharedModules("numpy"))){
            jep.eval("import numpy");
            jep.eval("numpy.array(1)");
        } catch (Exception e){
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }

}
```

The result of running the code:

```
jep.JepException: <class 'AttributeError'>: module 'numpy' has no attribute 'array'
	at <string>.<module>(<string>:1)
jep.JepException: <class 'AttributeError'>: module 'numpy' has no attribute 'array'
	at <string>.<module>(<string>:1)
jep.JepException: <class 'AttributeError'>: module 'numpy' has no attribute 'array'
	at <string>.<module>(<string>:1)
jep.JepException: <class 'AttributeError'>: module 'numpy' has no attribute 'array'
	at <string>.<module>(<string>:1)
jep.JepException: <class 'AttributeError'>: module 'numpy' has no attribute 'array'
	at <string>.<module>(<string>:1)
jep.JepException: <class 'AttributeError'>: module 'numpy' has no attribute 'array'
	at <string>.<module>(<string>:1)
jep.JepException: <class 'AttributeError'>: module 'numpy' has no attribute 'array'
	at <string>.<module>(<string>:1)
array(1)
array(1)
array(1)
```

As you can see the first 7 threads failed to lookup the attribute, however after numpy finished initializing the last 3 threads succeeded.
